  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)\n- Monitoring transactions for unusual patterns\n- Reporting suspicious transactions to authorities\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training staff on money laundering detection\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Currency Transaction Reporting\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Documenting large currency exchanges\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence for complex cases\n\n6. International Compliance\n- Following regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n7. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Potential significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Potential loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial systems from being used for illegal activities.",
